article.description: Jason Kidd had 26 points, 12 assists and 12 rebounds for his league-high sixth triple-double, and 44th of his career, to lead the New Jersey Nets to a 123-115 victory over the Golden State Warriors on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Nets prevail in high-scoring shootout

images.name: Kidd_Jason 020219 inline
images.caption: New Jersey's Jason Kidd gets one of his 12 rebounds, all part of his sixth triple-double of the season.

article.linkText: Kidd's triple-double lifts Nets past prolific Warriors
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- An NBA season-high 75 first-half points and Jason Kidd's sixth triple-double almost wasn't enough for the New Jersey Nets. Kidd had 26 points, 12 assists and 12 rebounds for the 44th triple-double of his career, and Kenyon Martin came up with a big, controversial block with 50.1 seconds to play as the Nets beat the Golden State Warriors 123-115 on Tuesday night. The game was a tale of two halves, as the Nets shot 60 percent in opening a 24-point halftime lead. They then seemed to take portions of the final 24 minutes off, allowing the Warriors to close to within three points in the final minute. "Things came so easy in the first half, we thought they would come as easy in the second half," Martin said. "We kind of slacked off and we picked it up again in the fourth." It almost wasn't enough. Golden State, which trailed by as many as 25, got within 116-113 on two free throws by Jason Richardson with 1:17 to play. After New Jersey's Keith Van Horn missed a 3-pointer on the ensuing possession, Richardson drove the lane after making a move from the left wing. However, his shot was blocked by Martin near the rim. The Warriors screamed at the officials, but no call was made. "I don't know if it was a goaltend," Warriors coach Brian Winters said. "It was a pretty close play. It could have gone either way."
All-time triple-double leaders
Player 3-Ds
Oscar Robertson 178
Magic Johnson 138
Wilt Chamberlain 74
Larry Bird 59
Jason Kidd 44
Fat Lever 43
Kerry Kittles hit two free throws with 45.2 seconds to play and Kidd hit another after Richardson missed another shot, and the Warriors never threatened again. "We always felt confident," Kidd said. "There's nothing wrong with that. But you have to shut the door with some confidence." Kidd called his triple-double, which made him the Nets' career leader in just a little more than a half-season, "another night at the office." Lucious Harris added 19 points as New Jersey finished with seven players in double figures in winning their third straight, and sending the Warriors to their eighth straight road loss and 16th in 17 games. Antawn Jamison and Richardson each had 25 points, and Larry Hughes added 20 and 13 assists for Golden State in the wild game that also featured 190 shots, 100 rebounds, 55 personal fouls and five technicals. Warriors forward Danny Fortson got two technicals midway through the third quarter and was ejected, leaving with 16 points and nine rebounds. New Jersey seemed on the verge of a runaway at the half. They used a 22-4 first-quarter spurt in building a 75-51 halftime lead. Golden State made a game of it with a 16-2 spurt to open the second half. Even Fortson's ejection didn't slow them down. Down 116-105 with 3:09 to go, Richardson scored six points in an 8-0 run to cut the lead to three, but Golden State never got closer. "We do that too often," Richardson said. "We dig ourselves a hole and we try to come back in the fourth quarter and just come up short. We have to be better in the first quarter." Kittles had 18 points for New Jersey.

Game notes
Kidd passed Kenny Anderson, who played five seasons with the Nets, as the team's career leader in triple-doubles. ... Nets center Todd MacCulloch missed his first game of the season with a sore foot. Rookie Jason Collins started and had 15 points and five rebounds. ... New Jersey is 8-1 vs. teams that it lost to in the first meeting of the season. Golden State won 101-85 on Nov. 25. ... It was the third straight game Golden State failed to become the seventh NBA franchise to win 2,000 games. ... Coming off a 1-4 homestand, the Warriors will play four road games in five days. They are 5-18 away from home. ... The 123 points was two shy of the Nets' season high. This marked the first time in nine games Golden State scored 100 points... Sacramento has the NBA season high for points in a half, scoring 78 in the second half against Phoenix on Dec. 23.
